<section class="intro-section mb-12">
    <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>Web Layout</strong> is a deliberately thin <strong>protocol-host</strong> standard: it owns
        exactly one Protocol &mdash; the <a href="#protocol-dockable-layout-tree">dockable layout-tree
        interchange</a> &mdash; and nothing else. It ships <em>no</em> implementation and <em>no</em>
        orchestration; the dock manager, drag-to-dock, and OS-window popout are
        <a href="/projects/frontierui/">Frontier UI</a> impl (#1511&ndash;#1514). The
        <a href="/intents/dockable/">dockable</a> intent and its realizing block stay <strong>project-less</strong>
        (per <a href="/backlog/1437-decision-docking-tiling-dockable-window-management-placement-/">#1437</a>
        Fork&nbsp;1); this project exists only because a first-class WE Protocol must resolve an
        <code>ownedByProject</code> (ratified <a href="/backlog/1653-which-project-owns-the-dockable-layout-tree-protocol-1437-ru/">#1653</a> (a)).
    </p>
</section>

<section id="protocol-dockable-layout-tree" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="protocol-heading">Protocol &mdash; <code>DockableLayoutTree</code></h3>
    <p>
        Standardizes the <strong>serialized partition tree</strong> that the surveyed dockable-window
        managers (<code>dockview</code>, FlexLayout, golden-layout) all emit, so a layout authored under one
        engine round-trips through another. The contract is the only lock; any conforming impl that
        round-trips the tree (the conformance criterion) interoperates. Source schema:
        <a href="/blocks/dockable/"><code>blocks/dockable/contract.ts</code></a> (<code>DockLayout</code>);
        the second conforming impl that cleared the convergence gate is the
        <a href="/backlog/1627-build-a-dockview-adapter-that-round-trips-the-dockable-core-/">dockview adapter</a>
        (#1627).
    </p>

    <div class="standards-grid">
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="protocol-core-schema" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Convergent core schema</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                A node is a <code>row</code> or <code>column</code> split (laying out <code>children</code>
                horizontally / vertically) or a <code>stack</code> leaf (a tab-stack of <code>tabs</code>
                panels). Nesting is arbitrary; space is fully partitioned (no gaps, no overlaps). Each
                node carries an optional <code>size</code> (<code>{ value, unit: ratio | pixel }</code>) within
                its parent split. This is the convergent shape across all three surveyed engines.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="protocol-extension-slot" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Open extension slot</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                The divergent encodings &mdash; popout-state (<code>popout: none | window</code>), per-panel
                metadata (<code>title</code> / <code>closable</code> / <code>activeTab</code>), and engine-specific
                constraints &mdash; ride an <strong>open extension slot</strong> layered on the core node,
                so a richer engine round-trips its own state without forking the convergent core.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="protocol-conformance" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Conformance &mdash; round-trip the tree</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                A conforming impl <strong>round-trips a <code>DockLayout</code></strong>: deserialize the
                core schema into its own model and re-serialize it without losing the partition topology,
                split sizes, or stack contents. The minimal round-trip vectors are a single
                <code>stack</code> root, a nested <code>row</code> of two <code>stack</code>s with
                <code>ratio</code> sizes, and a <code>column</code> wrapping a popout-tagged <code>stack</code>
                (the extension-slot survival case).
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
